  {
    "id": "src_antibiotic",
    "title": "Antibiotic",
    "url": "https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antibiotic",
    "summary": "",
    "categories": [],
    "topicIds": [
      "medicine"
    ],
    "articleText": null,
    "facts": [
      {
        "id": "fact_antibiotic_001",
        "text": "Ancient Sudanese societies as early as 350–550 CE were systematically consuming antibiotics as part of their diet.",
        "verified": true,
        "verifiedAt": "2026-04-11"
      },
      {
        "id": "fact_antibiotic_002",
        "text": "Chemical analyses of Nubian skeletons from northern Sudan show consistently high levels of tetracycline.",
        "verified": true,
        "verifiedAt": "2026-04-11"
      },
      {
        "id": "fact_antibiotic_003",
        "text": "Ancient Sudanese peoples are believed to have brewed beverages from grain fermented with Streptomyces, a bacterium that naturally produces tetracycline.",
        "verified": true,
        "verifiedAt": "2026-04-11"
      },
      {
        "id": "fact_antibiotic_004",
        "text": "The word 'antibiotic' literally means 'opposing life', derived from the Greek roots anti ('against') and bios ('life').",
        "verified": true,
        "verifiedAt": "2026-04-11"
      },
      {
        "id": "fact_antibiotic_005",
        "text": "Antibiotics produced naturally by one microorganism fighting another are distinct from fully synthetic antibacterials such as sulfonamides.",
        "verified": true,
        "verifiedAt": "2026-04-11"
      },
      {
        "id": "fact_antibiotic_006",
        "text": "Ancient civilizations including Egypt, China, Serbia, Greece, and Rome used topical application of moldy bread to treat infections.",
        "verified": true,
        "verifiedAt": "2026-04-11"
      },
      {
        "id": "fact_antibiotic_007",
        "text": "The first person to directly document the use of molds to treat infections was John Parkinson (1567–1650).",
        "verified": true,
        "verifiedAt": "2026-04-11"
      },
      {
        "id": "fact_antibiotic_008",
        "text": "Synthetic antibiotic chemotherapy as a science began in Germany with Paul Ehrlich in the late 1880s.",
        "verified": true,
        "verifiedAt": "2026-04-11"
      },
      {
        "id": "fact_antibiotic_009",
        "text": "Alexander Fleming discovered modern-day penicillin in 1928.",
        "verified": true,
        "verifiedAt": "2026-04-11"
      },
      {
        "id": "fact_antibiotic_010",
        "text": "The term 'antibiosis' was introduced by French bacteriologist Jean Paul Vuillemin.",
        "verified": true,
        "verifiedAt": "2026-04-11"
      },
      {
        "id": "fact_antibiotic_011",
        "text": "Antibiosis was first described in 1877 when Louis Pasteur and Robert Koch observed that an airborne bacillus could inhibit the growth of Bacillus anthracis.",
        "verified": true,
        "verifiedAt": "2026-04-11"
      },
      {
        "id": "fact_antibiotic_012",
        "text": "The drugs later called antibiotics were renamed as such by Selman Waksman, an American microbiologist, in 1947.",
        "verified": true,
        "verifiedAt": "2026-04-11"
      },
      {
        "id": "fact_antibiotic_013",
        "text": "The term 'antibiotic' was first used in 1942 by Selman Waksman and his collaborators in journal articles.",
        "verified": true,
        "verifiedAt": "2026-04-11"
      },
      {
        "id": "fact_antibiotic_014",
        "text": "Waksman's original 1942 definition of 'antibiotic' excluded substances not produced by microorganisms, such as gastric juices and hydrogen peroxide.",
        "verified": true,
        "verifiedAt": "2026-04-11"
      },
      {
        "id": "fact_antibiotic_015",
        "text": "Antibiotics are not effective against viruses, fungi, or the common cold or influenza.",
        "verified": true,
        "verifiedAt": "2026-04-11"
      },
      {
        "id": "fact_antibiotic_016",
        "text": "A limited number of antibiotics also possess antiprotozoal activity.",
        "verified": true,
        "verifiedAt": "2026-04-11"
      },
      {
        "id": "fact_antibiotic_017",
        "text": "Common side effects of oral antibiotics include diarrhea caused by disruption of the intestinal flora.",
        "verified": true,
        "verifiedAt": "2026-04-11"
      },
      {
        "id": "fact_antibiotic_018",
        "text": "Antibiotic-associated diarrhea can result from overgrowth of pathogenic bacteria such as Clostridioides difficile.",
        "verified": true,
        "verifiedAt": "2026-04-11"
      },
      {
        "id": "fact_antibiotic_019",
        "text": "Taking probiotics during antibiotic treatment can help prevent antibiotic-associated diarrhea.",
        "verified": true,
        "verifiedAt": "2026-04-11"
      },
      {
        "id": "fact_antibiotic_020",
        "text": "Antibiotics can affect vaginal flora and may lead to overgrowth of Candida yeast species.",
        "verified": true,
        "verifiedAt": "2026-04-11"
      },
      {
        "id": "fact_antibiotic_021",
        "text": "Adverse effects of antibiotics range from fever and nausea to anaphylaxis and photodermatitis.",
        "verified": true,
        "verifiedAt": "2026-04-11"
      },
      {
        "id": "fact_antibiotic_022",
        "text": "The bactericidal activity of antibacterials often requires ongoing metabolic activity and division of bacterial cells.",
        "verified": true,
        "verifiedAt": "2026-04-11"
      },
      {
        "id": "fact_antibiotic_023",
        "text": "In vitro characterization of antibacterial activity commonly includes determining the minimum inhibitory concentration and minimum bactericidal concentration.",
        "verified": true,
        "verifiedAt": "2026-04-11"
      },
      {
        "id": "fact_antibiotic_024",
        "text": "The term 'antibiotic' in current usage applies to any medication that kills or inhibits bacteria, regardless of whether it is produced by a microorganism.",
        "verified": true,
        "verifiedAt": "2026-04-11"
      }
    ],
    "questionIds": [
      "med_001"
    ]
  },
